recordings.loc: Maine (near  Saint George), Knox County, Maine
recordings.rmk:
This song is called several times over. The direction of the call is difficult to determine as the sound seems to be coming from all around - it is loud but somewhat haunting. The position seems to be in the mid to low canopy. The habitat is maritime coastal Maine: mostly spruce trees. This recording (and most songs) are heard just inland (maybe 1/8th of a mile). I have not seen the bird, although I did see a small (sparrow-robin sized) bird low in the canopy. It was completely brown with no distinct markings that could possibly be the bird making the sound. You can see the habitat here in the video recording:

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9ZLpFhsHRCI

recordings.rmk: I was working on the song for the whitethroatsong.ca project.  The white-striped morph bird was vocalizing in dense shrubbery with a chip note, and it was quiet enough to get a recording  disturbed only by the wind.

Natural sounds.

#Habitat#
State waterfowl refuge along the margins of USACE flood control reservoir. Strip along the lake margins ~1km wide of moist soil grassland with mix of forbs, native warm season grasses (Andropogon, Schyzachyrium, Eragrostis, Aristida, etc.), and some sparse woody vegetation (Cephalanthus, Quercus saplings, etc.) bounded by oak hickory forest and, in places, pine plantation.  Three or four shallow waterfowl impoundments partially flooded in the winter.

#Editing#
No edits.

#Equipment#
Fostex FR-2 digital recorder with Sennheiser microphone and Telinga pro 22" parabolic reflector.

recordings.rmk: I was watching and recording a number of birds in a bramble next to a field. Several sparrows were feeding in the brush, including White-throated Sparrow, Song Sparrow, Savannah Sparrow and White-crowned Sparrow. One White-throated Sparrow jumped up to the fence sounding the alarm calls recorded here. Other birds in the bramble were Northern Cardinal. In the tree nearby was Downy Woodpecker, Red-bellied Woodpecker and Northern Flicker.

Habitat: perched in a birch tree above me at the corner of my house

Environmental factors: overcast, yard work below the tree did not scare it away. For six weeks, a White-throated sparrow has been singing for a mate. Today, it was the first time that I have heard this chipping call. Did it find a mate? No, it found a plentiful food supply. Where? At the location of the former deck at my house. When it was torn down, it exposed carpenter ants from rotten portions of the deck.

recordings.loc: Corrales Bosque near Dixon Road, Sandoval County, New Mexico
recordings.rmk:
Call heard while walking trail along river, emanating from dense thicket. Heard it, attempted to record, bird went silent. Waited. Spend 30 minutes trying to track it down and got good recording ("video" on cell phone). Saw fleeting glimpse of it along with some White-crowned Sparrows that were foraging in same patch. Guy with unleashed dog came along, so that was that. Bird did not appear again but did vocalize. Both Myrtle and Audubon's Yellow-rumped Warblers in same area. Have never heard this vocalization before.
File was brought into Audacity, where audio was extracted. Minor notch filter applied. Two passes of Noise Filter then applied (from background sample). Volume enhanced mildly (it was pretty loud in the field). File exported as .mp3 (and .wav).

Flushed from tall grass. Distance from microphone ~4m.

#Habitat#
State waterfowl refuge along the margins of USACE flood control reservoir. Strip along the lake margins ~1km wide of moist soil grassland with mix of forbs, native warm season grasses (Andropogon, Schyzachyrium, Eragrostis, Aristida, etc.), and some sparse woody vegetation (Cephalanthus, Quercus saplings, etc.) bounded by oak hickory forest and, in places, pine plantation.  Three or four shallow waterfowl impoundments partially flooded in the winter.

#Editing#
Adobe Audition. Butterworth high-pass filter, cutoff 700 hz, order 3. 

#Equipment#
Fostex FR-2 digital recorder with Sennheiser microphone and Telinga pro 22" parabolic reflector.

recordings.rmk: I've typically heard this bird song in higher elevations around 3,700 feet (1,128 meters) around spring time (late March to early May), and I've never been able to identify the bird species or lay eyes on it. It is always common to hear this bird in Adirondacks in New York and the White Mountains in New Hampshire, but this year I've heard it for the first time at lower elevations for almost the entire month of April and the first week of November. I originally thought it was a "Field Sparrow" but I haven't heard any recordings of a Field Sparrow that match this song.
